description:
An essential water source in Gaza City is now contaminated with sewage and debris.
Israel’s two-year war destroyed pumps and drainage lines, turning a rainwater pond into hazardous waste.
Heavy rains have raised water levels, threatening displaced families in tents.
In Sheikh Radwan, water levels have risen six metres above normal, risking severe flooding.
Destroyed infrastructure means 400,000 cubic metres of water cannot be drained, raising disease risks.
Stagnant waters endanger children and worsen already dire winter conditions.
For hundreds of thousands of Palestinians, cold, flooding, and collapsing shelters add to their hardship.

Al Jazeera’s Ibrahim al-Khalili reports from Gaza City, Palestine.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
US Secretary of State Marco Rubio met Qatar's Prime Minister Sheikh Mohammed bin Abdulrahman Al Thani to discuss preserving the fragile Gaza ceasefire. 
Talks focused on Qatar's mediation role and advancing to the second stage of the US-led 20-point peace plan. Qatar’s PM stressed that aid must enter Gaza without conditions and that any stabilisation force must act impartially. 
Discussions included the force's potential role in disarming Hamas, though many obstacles remain. 
US officials hope to announce the force's composition early in the new year. It is proposed to consist largely of Indonesian and Turkish troops, raising concerns about language barriers with Arabic-speaking Palestinian residents of Gaza.

Al Jazeera’s Alan Fisher joins us live from Washington, DC to discuss the latest developments.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Devastated by decades of war and instability, Afghanistan is facing a multitude of crises.
Since the Taliban returned to power in 2021, it's been subjected to international sanctions.
Now, once again, Afghanistan is facing a severe humanitarian crisis.
The World Food Programme says it's unable to provide assistance to millions of Afghans.
It's the result of drastic cuts in aid funding by international donors.
The situation is compounded by the ongoing forced deportation of millions of Afghans from Pakistan and Iran.
So, how will these overlapping crises shape the future of the country -- and its people?


Presenter: Tom McRae

Guests:
Kiana Alavi -- Norwegian Refugee Council's advocacy manager in Afghanistan

Zeeshan Salahuddin -- Director Advisory of the Centre for Regional and Global Connectivity at Tabadlab

Obaidullah Baheer -- Adjunct Lecturer at the American University of Afghanistan and a peace and conflict resolution specialist

He detailed the severe risk of hypothermia and disease due to a lack of warm clothing and adequate shelter amidst a collapsed healthcare system. Cricks emphasised that living in tents for months is unsustainable and called for more permanent solutions. He noted that although the fragile ceasefire has allowed more aid to enter, the sheer scale of destruction remains the overwhelming challenge.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
In a besieged hospital in Gaza, Dr Hussam Abu Safia fights to save lives amid a blockade, personal tragedy and detention, triggering global calls for justice.

In the heart of Gaza’s war zone, Palestinian paediatrician Dr Hussam Abu Safia, former director of Kamal Adwan Hospital, became a symbol of courage when he walked towards an Israeli tank after being ordered to approach.

This award-winning documentary follows him and his wife Albina inside the besieged hospital, where their family lived for months after Israeli forces threatened their home. Facing a blockade on medicine, food, water and fuel, Abu Safia treated waves of war‑wounded patients, forced to choose who might live or die.

The cost was personal: his son Ibrahim was killed, another son Idris was injured, and the doctor himself was wounded. Yet he refused to leave. title: The Last Doctor Standing: Gaza’s doctor detained by Israel | Al Jazeera World documentary

It's the latest building to come down during the harsh winter storms in the Strip 
Civil defence teams rescued six members of a family, including two children, after the roof of their home caved in, in Shati refugee camp.
Hundreds of thousands of forcibly displaced Palestinians are sheltering in structurally unsafe buildings.
Israel is blocking the entry of mobile homes and sustainable shelters from Gaza in violation of the ceasefire it agreed with Hamas in October.
Authorities warn at least 500 buildings are at risk of collapse.

Al Jazeera’s Hind Khoudary is in Gaza City with the latest.

Shurouq is the Gaza Multimedia Manager for Save The Children. We are not disclosing her surname for safety reasons.

description:
US President Donald Trump is expanding a travel ban to five more countries and imposing new limits on others.
From January, citizens of Burkina Faso, Mali, Niger, South Sudan, and Syria will be banned from entering the US.  
They join 12 other countries that have been deemed “high-risk” including Afghanistan, Sudan, and Yemen.
The Trump administration has also imposed full restrictions on people with travel documents issued by the Palestinian Authority.

Al Jazeera’s Rosiland Jordan has more from Washington, DC.

description:
United States President Donald Trump has said he will sign an executive order labelling fentanyl and its core precursors as a “weapon of mass destruction” (WMD), in the latest instance of his administration using increasingly militarised language to justify its operations against drug cartels and smugglers.

Al Jazeera’s Mike Hanna reports from the White House in Washington, DC.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
A former senior US Drug Enforcement Administration official has rejected Donald Trump’s claim that fentanyl should be classified as a weapon of mass destruction, calling it political theatre rather than effective policy. Speaking to Al Jazeera, Michael Vigil said fentanyl overdoses are a public health and criminal justice issue, not an act of war, warning that such rhetoric could damage diplomatic relations and anti-narcotics cooperation.

Meanwhile, Al Jazeera’s Rosalind Jordan joins live from Washington, DC.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
The first funerals are being held for victims of the Bondi Beach shooting in Sydney, days after the deadly attack during a Hanukkah event. Among those remembered is Rabbi Eli Schlanger, a UK-born community leader who spent nearly two decades in Bondi and helped organise the event where the shooting occurred.

Al Jazeera’s Wayne Hay joins live from Bondi Beach, Sydney.

description:
Konya was where the Sufi poet Rumi made his home and left his spiritual legacy. It’s also a place where Silk Road spice traders have left their mark.

We visit Konya for the fourth episode of 'Traces of Silk', a five-part series that looks at the legacy of the ancient Silk Road in Turkiye and the impact that history still has today.
